---
import GuideLayout from '../components/layout/GuideLayout.astro';
import MonsterCard from '../components/ui/MonsterCard.astro';
import Callout from '../components/ui/Callout.astro';
import DataTable from '../components/ui/DataTable.astro';
import JsonLd from '../components/seo/JsonLd.astro';
import { darkCaveMonsters, basilisk } from '../data/monsters';

const allMonsters = [...darkCaveMonsters, basilisk];

const headings = [
  { depth: 2, slug: 'monster-classes', text: 'Monster Classes' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'dark-cave-monsters', text: 'Dark Cave Monsters' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'the-basilisk', text: 'The Basilisk' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'stat-comparison', text: 'Stat Comparison' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'elite-monsters', text: 'Elite Monsters' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'hunting-tips', text: 'Hunting Tips' },
];
---

<GuideLayout
  title="Creatures of the Wound"
  description="Complete bestiary for Ultimate Dominion's Dark Cave. All 11 monsters with stats, combat classes, drop tables, XP values, and tactical advice for every encounter."
  breadcrumbs={[{ label: 'Bestiary' }]}
  headings={headings}
>
  <JsonLd schema={{
    '@type': 'ItemList',
    name: 'Ultimate Dominion Bestiary — Dark Cave',
    description: 'All creatures found in the Dark Cave zone.',
    numberOfItems: allMonsters.length,
    dateModified: '2026-03-27',
    itemListElement: allMonsters.map((m, i) => ({
      '@type': 'ListItem',
      position: i + 1,
      name: `${m.name} (Level ${m.level} ${m.monsterClass})`,
    })),
  }} slot="head" />

  <h1>Creatures of the Wound</h1>
  <p class="text-lg text-text-secondary">
    The Dark Cave contains 11 monsters — one per level from 1 to 10, plus the Basilisk boss at level 12. Each belongs to one of three combat classes: Warrior (STR), Rogue (AGI), or Mage (INT). The class pattern alternates: Rogue, Mage, Warrior, Mage, Warrior, Rogue, Mage, Warrior, Rogue, Mage. Monster class determines combat triangle interactions — fighting with the triangle advantage grants up to +12% bonus damage.
  </p>
  <p class="text-xs text-text-secondary/60 mt-2">Last updated: March 2026</p>

  <h2 id="monster-classes">Monster Classes</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><em>Three classes: Warrior (STR, weak to INT), Rogue (AGI, weak to STR), Mage (INT, weak to AGI).</em></p>
  <p>
    Every monster belongs to one of three <a href="/guide/combat">combat classes</a>, determining its dominant stat and how the combat triangle applies:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Warrior (STR)</strong> — high HP and armor, hits hard. Weak to INT-based attackers.</li>
    <li><strong>Rogue (AGI)</strong> — fast and evasive, but fragile. Weak to STR-based attackers.</li>
    <li><strong>Mage (INT)</strong> — powerful magic, often ignoring armor. Weak to AGI-based attackers.</li>
  </ul>

  <Callout type="tip" title="Use the triangle">
    Before engaging, check the monster's class and compare it to your dominant stat. Fighting with the triangle advantage gives you +2% damage per stat point difference (up to 12%).
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="dark-cave-monsters">Dark Cave Monsters</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><em>Ten creatures, one per level (1-10), with alternating combat classes. Full stat cards and drop tables below.</em></p>
  <p>
    Ten regular creatures inhabit the Dark Cave, one per level from 1 to 10. The class sequence alternates irregularly — check the cards below for each monster's class.
  </p>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 not-prose my-6">
    {darkCaveMonsters.map((m) => (
      <MonsterCard
        name={m.name}
        level={m.level}
        monsterClass={m.monsterClass}
        hp={m.hp}
        str={m.str}
        agi={m.agi}
        int={m.int}
        armor={m.armor}
        xp={m.xp}
        drops={m.drops}
      />
    ))}
  </div>

  <h2 id="the-basilisk">The Basilisk</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><em>Level 12 boss with 130 HP, 4 armor, and dual-weapon boss AI. Drops only rare and epic gear.</em></p>
  <p>
    The Basilisk is the Dark Cave's boss encounter — a level 12 Warrior with boss AI. It attacks with <strong>Basilisk Fangs</strong> (physical + venom) and <strong>Petrifying Gaze</strong> (8-14 magic damage + venom). At 130 HP and 4 armor, this is a war of attrition.
  </p>

  <div class="not-prose my-6">
    <MonsterCard
      name={basilisk.name}
      level={basilisk.level}
      monsterClass={basilisk.monsterClass}
      hp={basilisk.hp}
      str={basilisk.str}
      agi={basilisk.agi}
      int={basilisk.int}
      armor={basilisk.armor}
      xp={basilisk.xp}
      drops={basilisk.drops}
    />
  </div>

  <Callout type="warning" title="Boss AI">
    The Basilisk uses boss AI — it switches between physical and magical attacks, applying venom with both. Intelligence builds have the triangle advantage, but bring Antidotes and plenty of healing.
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="stat-comparison">Stat Comparison</h2>

  <DataTable headers={['Monster', 'Lvl', 'Class', 'HP', 'STR', 'AGI', 'INT', 'Armor', 'XP']} compact>
    {allMonsters.map((m) => (
      <tr class="hover:bg-surface/50">
        <td class="px-3 py-2 text-white font-medium text-sm">{m.name}</td>
        <td class="px-3 py-2 font-mono text-xs text-center">{m.level}</td>
        <td class="px-3 py-2 text-xs text-center">{m.monsterClass}</td>
        <td class="px-3 py-2 font-mono text-xs text-center text-accent">{m.hp}</td>
        <td class="px-3 py-2 font-mono text-xs text-center text-red">{m.str}</td>
        <td class="px-3 py-2 font-mono text-xs text-center text-green">{m.agi}</td>
        <td class="px-3 py-2 font-mono text-xs text-center text-accent-gold">{m.int}</td>
        <td class="px-3 py-2 font-mono text-xs text-center">{m.armor}</td>
        <td class="px-3 py-2 font-mono text-xs text-center">{m.xp}</td>
      </tr>
    ))}
  </DataTable>

  <h2 id="elite-monsters">Elite Monsters</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><em>15% chance to spawn as elite — 1.3x stats, 1.5x HP, 2x drop chance, 1.5x XP/gold.</em></p>
  <p>
    Any monster can spawn as an <strong>elite variant</strong>. Elites have boosted stats and better rewards:
  </p>
  <DataTable headers={['Modifier', 'Value']}>
    <tr class="hover:bg-surface/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">Spawn chance</td><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">15%</td></tr>
    <tr class="hover:bg-surface/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">STR/AGI/INT</td><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">&times;1.3</td></tr>
    <tr class="hover:bg-surface/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">HP</td><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">&times;1.5</td></tr>
    <tr class="hover:bg-surface/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">XP &amp; Gold reward</td><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">&times;1.5</td></tr>
    <tr class="hover:bg-surface/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">Drop chance bonus</td><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">&times;2.0</td></tr>
  </DataTable>

  <h2 id="hunting-tips">Hunting Tips</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><em>Start with Dire Rats, farm Bugbears for weapons, prep consumables for the Hook Horror and Basilisk.</em></p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Start with Dire Rats</strong> — level 1, low HP (10), drops starter gear. Perfect for your first fights.</li>
    <li><strong>Farm the Bugbear</strong> — level 8 Warrior drops multiple weapons (Warhammer, Stone Maul) and Carved Stone Plate, making it one of the best farming targets for gear upgrades.</li>
    <li><strong>Hook Horror is the gate boss</strong> — level 10, 52 HP, 15 INT, and 2 armor. Come prepared with your best gear and a full stack of potions. Drops epic and rare gear from every class.</li>
    <li><strong>The Basilisk is endgame</strong> — 130 HP, boss AI, dual-weapon attacks with venom. Bring Antidotes, Greater Health Potions, and your best combat consumables. Drops only rare and epic items.</li>
    <li><strong>Watch the class pattern</strong> — R, M, W, M, W, R, M, W, R, M. Plan your consumable usage around upcoming encounters.</li>
  </ul>

  <Callout type="lore">
    The creatures were not always here. When Noctum fell, his death ripped a wound in reality. Things that should not exist crawled through — not from another place, but from the space between places. They do not eat, they do not sleep. They simply are.
  </Callout>
</GuideLayout>
